RT user can change it).<br /><br />The kernel has always done a certain amount of "default policy". <br /><br />What do you think things like "swappiness" etc are? Or things like <br />oevrcommit settings? They're all policies, and there is always a default <br />one. So in that sense the kernel always has - and fundamentally _must_ - <br />set some kind of policy.<br /><br />And the default policy should generally be the one that makes sense for <br />most people. Quite frankly, if it's an issue where all normal distros <br />would basically be expected to set a value, then that value should _be_ <br />the default policy, and none of the normal distros should ever need to <br />worry.<br /><br />Whether this case is one such, I dunno. Quite frankly, I don't think it's <br />even _nearly_ important enough to get this kind of noise.<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
